Heat a splash of @oil{a splash} in a large #frying pan{} over medium-high heat. Add the @cherry plum tomatoes{200}. Cook, stirring occasionally until softened slightly, ~{3%minutes}. Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}.

Add to the frying pan along with half the @Louisiana style spice mix{1} and cook, stirring occasionally, until softened, ~{5%minutes}.

Roughly chop the @coriander{10}(roughly chopped). Drain and rinse the @black beans{1} and @sweetcorn{326}. Keep to one side. Zest and halve the @lime{1}. Mix half the zest with the @soured cream{150}.

Pop the @21 day aged British rump steaks{240} onto a #plate{}. Season with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and the remaining Louisiana style spice mix. Add a splash of @oil{a splash} and rub the seasonings into the meat. Heat another frying pan on high heat (no oil!), we'll use this for the steak in a minute when it is very hot.

Add the beans and sweetcorn to the frying pan with the vegetables. Lower the heat to medium and cook for another ~{5%minutes}.

> Add a splash of water if the mixture is too dry.

Meanwhile, add the steak to your hot frying pan. Brown on each side for ~{1%minute}. Lower the heat to medium and cook for another ~{1-2%minutes} on each side for medium rare.

> Cook for 2 mins longer on each side if you want your steak more well done.

When cooked, move the steak onto a #board{}. Stir the remaining lime zest, lime juice and coriander into the jumble. Slice the steak and serve on top with a drizzle of the zesty @zesty sour cream{half the sour cream with lime zest}.

> Is there anything better than a perfectly cooked steak on the table in 20 minutes? We couldn't think of anything either. When cooking your steaks, avoid the temptation to turn them over before they've had the chance to colour nicely. Resting your steaks for 5 mins after cooking will allow the juices to spread evenly through the meat, giving it a richer and more succulent flavour. When you can get full on flavour in double quick time you know you're onto a winner.